Author: Blauelf#6622
Content:
Technically, triple quotes mark a multi-line string literal. So triple quotes have to match indentation, while comments don't, as they are ignored. Indentation mismatches can have confusing error messages, locating the problem after the wrongly-indented code.

In certain places of the code, multi-line string literals are used as docstrings (see [PEP 257](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0257/)), note that the text was written long before Python3, so some details might be outdated).

In other places, I prefer regular `#` style comments (as my IDE colours them as comments), not sure if that preference is meeting what's considered Pythonic.

Content: `return` ends the program if in `main` (since `main` is the main function of the program)

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: You've declared `int i = 0;`  and then, within the `do while` you've declared another `int i`  so the compiler is warning you in case you meant those two `i` variables to be the same one.  (in which case, you should simply say `i = get_int ...`  instead of `int i = get_int...`)

char* outfile = 000;

is same as
```c
char *outfile = NULL;
```
you probably should declare it as array, and `sprintf` the right filename into it.

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content:
There is no FAT in this image. And even if it was, you would not have to care about it.
You pass `NULL` to `fopen`, `fopen` tries to dereference the pointer (as it thinks there's a file name) and segfaults.
I had something like `char filename[8];` and would use `sprintf` to write the file name (7 characters plus null terminator, therefore 8 elements in the array)

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content:
All right, potentially dumb question. I'm working on speller and I'd like to know how to make a conditional checking whether a node's value is empty or not, I tried this:
```C
if(hashtable[i]->word == NULL)
```
And get the error
`comparison of array 'hashtable[i]->word' equal to a null pointer is always false`
How do you determine whether or not a string has no characters in it?

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: The node was already malloced so it makes sense that the string being equal to NULL would always be false

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: the only reason you'd malloc a node is to hold a word, so when would you ever need to check if it was empty or not?

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: For the first node in the hash table

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: All the nodes for the first nodes are malloced

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: Like the problem comes with code that already mallocs the hash table itself, the array of nodes, and those nodes have empty values

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: I wanted to fill in the empty values of those nodes to not have a node with no value in the list, for efficiency's sake

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: But it's probably insignificant enough to overlook

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: As long as I can free the whole list anyway... It's just a waste of memory is all

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: there is no code that mallocs all the first nodes, unless you've added that code yourself

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: the hashtable is an array of node pointers

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: that are all set to null (because no nodes have been malloced yet)

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: you should only malloc a node once you have a word to add to the table

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: Ohhh. I think I understand

Author: Kontrary#1502
Content: So the elements in the hash table are pointers to nodes and aren't nodes themselves

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: that's right.  `node *hashtable[N]`  declares an array of node pointers

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: each of which represents the head of a linked list

Otherwise, if it's pset-related, each problem has its own channel, but avoid posting solution code, and any large snippets should be marked as spoiler.

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content:
@!knd6060 The problem might be with the `messages=[]` default, I have seen this with stand-alone functions, but would probably be the same with methods. It is evaluated once on creating the function object, and all the calls to the constructor share this one list object.
A common work-around would be to use something like `messages=None`, and inside the function check for that one.

Author: jpjthunder#0746
Content:
```py
class Account:   #Account blueprint
    def __init__(self,name,password,isloged):
        self.name = ""
        self.password = ""
        self.isloged = False
    def say():
        msg = input()
        print(name+msg)


def start():            
    while True:                        #keeps it in a loop
        cmd = input()
        if cmd == "/register":      #register

            print("Name:")
            namer = input()

            print("Password:")
            passwordr = input()

            print("Are you sure you want to make this acount?")
            c = input()

            if c == "Yes":
                Account1 = Account(namer,passwordr,False)    #store acount data
                print("Name:"+namer+"\nPassword:"+passwordr)

        try:                                                                 #try block incase no account
            if cmd == "/login":
                if Account1.isloged == False:

                    print("Name:")
                    namel = input()

                    print("Password")
                    passwordl = input()
                    if namel == Account1.name:
                        if passwordl == Account1.password:
                            Account1.isloged == True

                else:
                    print("You are already logged in")
        except:
            print("You have no account yet.")
        
        try:
            if cmd == "/info":
                print(Account1.name,Account1.password,Account1.isloged)
            if cmd == "/say":
                Account1.say()
        except:
            print("You have no account.")

start()
 ```

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: and that's because when you divide the long  `4003600000000016/100000`  that would give you `40036000000`    and that number in binary is `1001 01100101 10100100 10111010 00000000`

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: but that number has 36 bits

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: and an int can only hold 32 bits

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so the top 4 bits are dropped when it's put into your integer `digit11`

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: and that means it now has the value `01100101 10100100 10111010 00000000`

Content: at first glance, you can make your power function much more efficient. Instead of what you're doing right now, i would use the fact that x^n == x^(n/2)  *   x^(n/2). As you can see, we can also compute x^(n/2) just once, allowing us to save a little bit of computation power. This would make your power function be O(log n) instead of O(n) i think

Author: Sanath#7244

Author: I_know_things#8723

Author: Sanath#7244
Content: I would have made a recursive solution. For even values of n you can do power(num, rest_to/2) * power(num, rest_to/2) and a similar one for odd values of n. The trick to improving efficiency is to only calculate power(num, n) once for any n. you can store the results in an array to prevent recomputation. It increases your storage cost but reduces your time

Author: ozay#4545
Content: Hello guys , I wanted to post up my code to see if any one could tell me whats wrong I am pretty sure I have the general concept correct but for some reason my nested for loop wont run

Author: ozay#4545
Content: for some reason my 2nd for loop and 3rd for loop wont run its code and the code totally skips it for some reason

Author: kadavraverkisto#7943
Content: @ozay The condition in the for-cycle is not when the cycle will stop but when it will _not_ stop. So, the outer cycle continues while i < height, and that's okay, because the initial value 1 can be less than height and it will reach it at some iteration. But the inner cycles start with the counter set to some (non-zero) value, check if it is _equal_ to 0, find that it is not and leave the cycle without even entering it once.

Content:
Can someone help me with this? After several hours trying to solve this problem, I turned to the Google search engine, so I could understand more or less that a for loop is composed.

The question is, on line 15, we are practically defining Espacios as the result of the subtraction of UsuarioEscribio-Espacios-1, and the condition given is that if Espacios is greater than 0, then it will subtract.

My question is, suppose that the user in his input defines UsuarioEscribio as 8, above we already have a for loop that defines Fila as 8 as well, as we have attached it to the UsuarioEscribio value. It is not supposed then, that the loop for Espacios, is 0 (8-8) and -1 would be -1, why then this works?

Author: Anya L#2162
Content: @Jose RTP7958 Fila is not 8. Fila is strarting out as 0 (it literally says Fila = 0), goes through the first iteration (everything between lines 15 and 23) as 0, then changes to 1, goes again, etc until it's 8. When it's 8, it's equal to UsuarioEscribio, so the condition for ending the loop is satisfied, and the program goes to line 25, bypassing lines 15-23, straight to the end of function

Author: Jose RTP7958#1690
Content: Then this could also work great, simply with a:

Content: for (int Espacios = UsuarioEscribio - 1; Espacios > 0; Espacios--) // spaces

Content:
I am in a bit of a brain freeze: I need to grab values from a list of dictionaries. I am fine with a nested for loop but I'd like to refactor it using list comprehensions, any hint?
```python
nested_list = [
    {
        "model": "Volvo 142E",
        "mpg": 21.4,
        "cyl": 4,
        "disp": 121,
        "hp": 109,
        "drat": 4.11,
        "wt": 2.78,
        "qsec": 18.6,
        "vs": 1,
        "am": 1,
        "gear": 4,
        "carb": 2 
    },
    {
        "model": "Maserati Bora",
        "mpg": 15,
        "cyl": 8,
        "disp": 301,
        "hp": 335,
        "drat": 3.54,
        "wt": 3.57,
        "qsec": 14.6,
        "vs": 0,
        "am": 1,
        "gear": 5,
        "carb": 8
    }
]

elems = []
for i in nested_list:
    for k, v in i.items():
        elems.append(v)
```

Author: andodet#3207
Content:
Okay, I am probably just tired, just figured it out myself. Here's the solution for anyone interested:
```python
[[elems.append(v) for k, v in d.items()] for d in nested_list]
```

Content:

from functools import reduce


elems = reduce(lambda l, i: [*l, *i.values()], nested_list, '')

```

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content: Python uses indentation through leading tabs or spaces, at the beginning of a line. I set my own editor to turn tabs into 4 spaces. Python does not care whether tabs or spaces (and how many) as long as it's consistent. PEP8 recommends spaces, and that's what `style50` will try to apply.

Content: @drail159 Thank you. Also is making programs as "modular" as possible usually a good idea? Like for example I made those 4 functions for what easily could've just been written directly in main, but I feel this is cleaner and more scalable?

Author: drail159#6376
Content: Yeah. That will make your code easier to read, maintain and reuse. For small projects it may not seem necessary to separate your code that way but it helps you to build good habits.

Author: drail159#6376
Content: Modular code is often easier to debug as well because if you get an compile time error for example then you can see what function it's in and you end up with less code to go through than if it was all just in main().

Author: tony thot aka scotty mcthotty#2976
Content: Is it a good idea to make every variable a const unless the value will change? I rarely see people do that but it seems logical to me.

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content: In JavaScript, that's a trend now that there's `let` and `const` (declaring block-scoped variables or constants), variables are sometimes replaced with throw-away constants. But there the constant is a guaranteed thing, and can help the compiler. In C, it's more a "I promise not to change the value... probably", you have to be somewhat explicit to change the value and might get a compiler warning, but I guess the compiler can't profit from that very much, it's more about making the developer realise they are probably doing something wrong.

Author: ./S.A#6274
Content:
First attempt at writing selection sort after watching the abstract tutorial by David Malan in the cs50 lecture of algorithms.

Reviews please? Criticism would be appreciated

```def selection_sort(lst):
	l = len(lst)
	
	for i in range(l):
		
		# finding smallest element from position i to end of list
		smallest = lst[i]
		index_of_smallest = i
		for j in range(i+1, l):
			if lst[j] < smallest:
				smallest = lst[j]
				index_of_smallest = j
		
		#if i'th element isn't equal to the smallest, then swap the smallest elememt with ith element
		if lst[i] != lst[index_of_smallest]:
			lst[i], lst[index_of_smallest] = lst[index_of_smallest], lst[i]
 ```

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content: You could even do `if i != index_of_smallest`, if there are more occurrences you use the first one, so if those values are equal, the index is, too.

Author: expressive#4411
Content: I'm working on something in python- basic code that does linear regression. I want to know how to make this code more python-like, if that makes sense. It feels like I'm just copying C style here.

Author: expressive#4411
Content:
`import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Initial values
x_values = [1, 2, 4, 3, 5]
y_values = [1, 3, 3, 2, 5]

b0 = 0
b1 = 0
alpha = 0.01
epochs = 4 # An epoch is a complete pass through the training dataset
error = None

# Underscore in Python is assigned to a value that you're not going to use
for _ in range(0, epochs):
    for i in range(0, len(x_values)):
        predicted_result = b0 + b1 * x_values[i]
        # error = predicted - actual
        error = predicted_result - y_values[i]
        b0 = b0 - alpha * error
        b1 = b1 - alpha * error * x_values[i]

print(b0)
print(b1)

`

Author: pylang#6845
Content: @expressive Your code already looks pretty pythonic.  It's custom to iterate a sequence rather than mess with indices.  If you need indices, use `enumerate()`.

Author: pylang#6845
Content: A couple optional other shortcuts: tuple unpacking and decrementers

Author: pylang#6845
Content:
```python
b0, b1 = 0, 0
...
    ... i, _ in enumerate(x_values):
        ...
        b0 -= alpha * error
        b1 -= alpha * error * x_values[i]
```

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content: Maybe use `zip(x_values, y_values)` as the iterator.

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content:
Like
```Python
    for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values):
```

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content: `zip` returns an iterator that provides tuples with one element of each iterable, until any of them is at the end. There's also a version `zip_longest` that in this case would fill the empty spots with some value. Wouldn't matter if all the lists are of same length.

Author: Lukas#2338
Content: Also, when `range` is only given one argument, like `range(n)`, it will have the same behaviour as `range(0, n)`.

Author: Lukas#2338
Content: So you can repace `range(0, epochs)` with just `range(epochs)`

Content: True, totally missed that.

Content: why my code works if list already has first element and when I try to create it via this function (else block) it returns segmentation fault when trying to print elements of the list

Author: Blauelf#6622
Content:
@Nihil Novi Arguments are passed by value. So `list` contains the *value* passed to the function, it is in no way connected to the variable used to store that value on the calling side.
There are usually two ways in that case: Either return the new list head, or pass a pointer to the head pointer instead. The copied pointer to pointer would still point to the same pointer to node.

Author: 220284hk#8165
curiouskiwi#1671
Content: In C, an array variable "decays" to a pointer as needed.  it holds the address of the first byte of the array.

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so if a function needs a pointer, you can pass it the name of an array and it will work.

Author: 220284hk#8165
Content: I think I understand what you mean but isn't x already an address in this case? If we do &x wouldn't that be an address of an address?

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: you'd think that, but no.  it's a special case for arrays in C that if you ask for the address of the array, you get the same value as if you print the address of the variable ... because when you do that, it 'decays' to the address.

Author: 220284hk#8165
Content: Ah okay... which one is more aesthetically pleasing/widely accepted? Using x or &x?

Author: Berky_Ross#6951
Content: > It will be at least as big as sizeof (int) plus sizeof (struct Node *), and potentially may be bigger; depending on your platform, it could be as small as 4 bytes or as large as 16. C allows for "padding" bytes between struct members to satisfy alignment requirements for the underlying architecture. For example, a particular architecture may require that all multi-byte objects be aligned on addresses that are multiples of 4; if your data member is only 2 bytes wide, then there will be 2 unused bytes between it and the next member.

Let's suppose I'm checking if there are repetitions in and array of chars.

Author: coldfusion#5932
Content:
@Raphael Marques 
you start off printing 3 \* 3 when you set n = 3 and q = 3
in the first loop, double a = q\*n sets a to 3\*3 when you input n = 3 and q=3 then 
in the second while loop you print a \* n which is 9 \*3 since a was initialized to 3 *3 
after all of that, the loops run again but no number was incremented/changed so it just does the same calculations again and prints the same values
